# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-looker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Organizations may apply analytics to business data to describe, predict, and improve business performance.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Specifically, areas within analytics include descriptive analytics, diagnostic analytics, predictive analytics, prescriptive analytics, and cognitive analytics.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Analytics may apply to a variety of fields such as marketing, management, finance, online systems, information security, and software services.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Since analytics can require extensive computation (see big data), the algorithms and software used for analytics harness the most current methods in computer science, statistics, and mathematics.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] According to International Data Corporation, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] As per Gartner, the overall analytic platforms software market grew by $25.5 billion in 2020.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Data analysis focuses on the process of examining past data through business understanding, data understanding, data preparation, modeling and evaluation, and deployment.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] It is a subset of data analytics, which takes multiple data analysis processes to focus on why an event happened and what may happen in the future based on the previous data.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Data analytics is used to formulate larger organizational decisions.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Data analytics is a multidisciplinary field.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] There is extensive use of computer skills, mathematics, statistics, descriptive techniques, and predictive models to gain valuable knowledge from data through analytics.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] It also includes unsupervised machine learning techniques like cluster analysis, principal component analysis, segmentation profile analysis, and association analysis.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Marketing organizations use analytics to evaluate the outcomes of campaigns and initiatives, as well as to guide decisions related to investment and consumer targeting.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Techniques such as demographic studies, customer segmentation, conjoint analysis, and others enable marketers to analyze large volumes of consumer purchase data, survey data, and panel data.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] This helps them better understand consumer behavior and effectively communicate marketing strategies.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Marketing analytics consists of both qualitative and quantitative, structured and unstructured data used to drive strategic decisions about brand and revenue outcomes.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The process involves predictive modelling, marketing experimentation, automation, and real-time sales communications.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The data enables companies to make predictions and alter strategic execution to maximize performance results.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Web analytics allows marketers to collect session-level information about interactions on a website using an operation called sessionization.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Google Analytics is an example of a popular free analytics tool that marketers use for this purpose.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Those interactions provide web analytics information systems with the information necessary to track the referrer, search keywords, identify the IP address, and track the activities of the visitor.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] With this information, a marketer can improve marketing campaigns, website creative content, and information architecture.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Analysis techniques frequently used in marketing include marketing mix modeling, pricing and promotion analyses, sales force optimization, and customer analytics, e.g., segmentation.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Web analytics and optimization of websites and online campaigns now frequently work hand in hand with the more traditional marketing analysis techniques.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] A focus on digital media has slightly changed the vocabulary so that *marketing mix modeling* is commonly referred to as *attribution modeling* in the digital or marketing mix modeling context.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] People analytics uses behavioral data to understand how people work and change how companies are managed.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] It can be referred to by various names, depending on the context, the purpose of the analytics, or the specific focus of the analysis.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Some examples include workforce analytics, HR analytics, talent analytics, people insights, talent insights, colleague insights, human capital analytics, and human resources information system (HRIS) analytics.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] HR analytics is the application of analytics to help companies manage human resources.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] HR analytics has become a strategic tool in analyzing and forecasting human-related trends in the changing labor markets, using career analytics tools.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The aim is to discern which employees to hire, which to reward or promote, what responsibilities to assign, and similar human resource problems.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] For example, inspection of the strategic phenomenon of employee turnover utilizing people analytics tools may serve as an important analysis at times of disruption.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] It has been suggested that people analytics is a separate discipline to HR analytics, with a greater focus on addressing business issues, while HR Analytics is more concerned with metrics related to HR processes.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Additionally, people analytics may now extend beyond the human resources function in organizations.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] However, experts find that many HR departments are burdened by operational tasks and need to prioritize people analytics and automation to become a more strategic and capable business function in the evolving world of work, rather than producing basic reports that offer limited long-term value.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Some experts argue that a change in the way HR departments operate is essential.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Although HR functions were traditionally centered on administrative tasks, they are now evolving with a new generation of data-driven HR professionals who serve as strategic business partners.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Examples of HR analytic metrics include employee lifetime value (ELTV), labour cost expense percent, union percentage, etc.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] **Quality of promotion** is a metric used to assess a person's promotion decisions.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The metric determines whether employees appropriately advanced on objective criteria rather or if a bias is present.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] A common application of business analytics is portfolio analysis.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] In this, a bank or lending agency has a collection of accounts of varying value and risk.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The accounts may differ by the social status (wealthy, middle-class, poor, etc.) of the holder, the geographical location, its net value, and many other factors.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The lender must balance the return on the loan with the risk of default for each loan.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The question is then how to evaluate the portfolio as a whole.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The least risk loan may be to the very wealthy, but there are a very limited number of wealthy people.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] On the other hand, there are many poor that can be lent to, but at greater risk.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Some balance must be struck that maximizes return and minimizes risk.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The analytics solution may combine time series analysis with many other issues in order to make decisions on when to lend money to these different borrower segments, or decisions on the interest rate charged to members of a portfolio segment to cover any losses among members in that segment.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Predictive models in the banking industry are developed to bring certainty across the risk scores for individual customers.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Credit scores are built to predict an individual's delinquency behavior and are widely used to evaluate the credit worthiness of each applicant.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Furthermore, risk analyses are carried out in the scientific world and the insurance industry.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] It is also extensively used in financial institutions like online payment gateway companies to analyse if a transaction was genuine or fraud.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] For this purpose, they use the transaction history of the customer.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] This is more commonly used in Credit Card purchases, when there is a sudden spike in the customer transaction volume the customer gets a call of confirmation if the transaction was initiated by him/her.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] This helps in reducing loss due to such circumstances.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Digital analytics is a set of business and technical activities that define, create, collect, verify, or transform digital data into reporting, research, analyses, recommendations, optimizations, predictions, and automation.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] This also includes SEO (search engine optimization), where the keyword search is tracked and that data is used for marketing purposes, and banner ad clicks.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] A growing number of brands and marketing firms rely on digital analytics for their digital marketing assignments, where marketing return on investment (MROI) is an important key performance indicator (KPI).
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Security analytics refers to information technology (IT) to gather security events to understand and analyze events that pose the greatest security risks.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Products in this area include security information and event management and user behavior analytics.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Software analytics is the process of collecting information about the way a piece of software is used and produced.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] In the industry of commercial analytics software, an emphasis has emerged on solving the challenges of analyzing massive, complex data sets, often when such data is in a constant state of change.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Such data sets are commonly referred to as big data.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Whereas once the problems posed by big data were only found in the scientific community, today big data is a problem for many businesses that operate transactional systems online and, as a result, amass large volumes of data quickly.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] The analysis of unstructured data types is another challenge getting attention in the industry.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Unstructured data differs from structured data in that its format varies widely and cannot be stored in traditional relational databases without significant effort at data transformation.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Sources of unstructured data, such as email, the contents of word processor documents, PDFs, geospatial data, etc., are rapidly becoming a relevant source of business intelligence for businesses, governments, and universities.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] These challenges are the current inspiration for much of the innovation in modern analytics information systems, giving birth to relatively new machine analysis concepts such as complex event processing, full text search and analysis, and even new ideas in presentation.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] One such innovation is the introduction of grid-like architecture in machine analysis, allowing increases in the speed of massively parallel processing by distributing the workload to many computers all with equal access to the complete data set.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Analytics is increasingly used in education, particularly at the district and government office levels.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] However, the complexity of student performance measures presents challenges when educators try to understand and use analytics to discern patterns in student performance, predict graduation likelihood, improve chances of student success, etc.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] For example, in a study involving districts known for strong data use, 48% of teachers had difficulty posing questions prompted by data, 36% did not comprehend given data, and 52% incorrectly interpreted data.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] To combat this, some analytics tools for educators adhere to an over-the-counter data format (embedding labels, supplemental documentation, and a help system, and making key package/display and content decisions) to improve educators' understanding and use of the analytics being displayed.
[src:gcp-looker/analytics] Risks for the general population include discrimination on the basis of characteristics such as gender, skin colour, ethnic origin, or political opinions through mechanisms such as price discrimination or statistical discrimination.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] BI tools can handle large amounts of structured and sometimes unstructured data to help organizations identify, develop, and otherwise create new strategic business opportunities.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] They aim to allow for the easy interpretation of these big data.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Identifying new opportunities and implementing an effective strategy based on insights is assumed to potentially provide businesses with a competitive market advantage and long-term stability, and help them take strategic decisions.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Business intelligence can be used by enterprises to support a wide range of business decisions ranging from operational to strategic.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Basic operating decisions include product positioning or pricing.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Strategic business decisions involve priorities, goals, and directions at the broadest level.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In all cases, business intelligence is considered most effective when it combines data from the market in which a company operates (external data) with data from internal company sources, such as financial and operational information.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] When integrated, external and internal data provide a comprehensive view that creates ‘intelligence’ not possible from any single data source alone.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Among their many uses, business intelligence tools empower organizations to gain insight into new markets, to assess demand and suitability of products and services for different market segments, and to gauge the impact of marketing efforts.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] BI applications use data gathered from a data warehouse (DW) or from a data mart, and the concepts of BI and DW combine as "BI/DW" or as "BIDW".
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] A data warehouse contains a copy of analytical data that facilitates decision support.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] The earliest known use of the term *business intelligence* is in Richard Millar Devens' *Cyclopædia of Commercial and Business Anecdotes* (1865).
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] The ability to collect and react accordingly based on the information retrieved, Devens says, is central to business intelligence.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In 1989, Howard Dresner (later a Gartner analyst) proposed *business intelligence* as an umbrella term to describe "concepts and methods to improve business decision making by using fact-based support systems." It was not until the late 1990s that this usage was widespread.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Therefore, Forrester refers to *data preparation* and *data usage* as two separate but closely linked segments of the business-intelligence architectural stack.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] If understood broadly, competitive intelligence can be considered as a subset of business intelligence.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Business intelligence and business analytics are sometimes used interchangeably, but there are alternate definitions.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Thomas Davenport, professor of information technology and management at Babson College argues that business intelligence should be divided into querying, reporting, Online analytical processing (OLAP), an "alerts" tool, and business analytics.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In this definition, business analytics is the subset of BI focusing on statistics, prediction, and optimization, rather than the reporting functionality.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Business operations can generate a very large amount of data in the form of emails, memos, notes from call centers, news, user groups, chats, reports, web pages, presentations, image files, video files, and marketing material.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] According to Merrill Lynch, more than 85% of all business information exists in these forms; a company might only use such a document a single time.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Because of the way it is produced and stored, this information is either unstructured or semi-structured.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] The management of semi-structured data is an unsolved problem in the information technology industry.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] According to projections from Gartner (2003), white-collar workers spend 30–40% of their time searching, finding, and assessing unstructured data.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] BI uses both structured and unstructured data.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] The former is easy to search, and the latter contains a large quantity of the information needed for analysis and decision-making.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Because of the difficulty of properly searching, finding, and assessing unstructured or semi-structured data, organizations may not draw upon these vast reservoirs of information, which could influence a particular decision, task, or project.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] This can ultimately lead to poorly informed decision-making.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Therefore, when designing a business intelligence/DW solution, the specific problems associated with semi-structured and unstructured data must be accommodated, as well as those associated with structured data.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] There are several challenges to developing BI with semi-structured data.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] To solve problems with searchability and assessment of data, it is necessary to know something about the content.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] This can be done by adding context through the use of metadata.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Many systems already capture some metadata (e.g. filename, author, size, etc.), but more useful would be metadata about the actual content – e.g. summaries, topics, people, or companies mentioned.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Two technologies designed for generating metadata about content are automatic categorization and information extraction.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Generative business intelligence is the application of generative AI techniques, such as large language models, in business intelligence.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] This combination facilitates data analysis and enables users to interact with data more intuitively, generating actionable insights through natural language queries.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Microsoft Copilot was, for example, integrated into the business analytics tool Power BI.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In a 2013 report, Gartner categorized business intelligence vendors as either an independent "pure-play" vendor or a consolidated "mega-vendor".
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In 2019, the BI market was shaken within Europe for the new legislation of GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) which puts the responsibility of data collection and storage onto the data user with strict laws in place to make sure the data is compliant.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Growth within Europe has steadily increased since May 2019 when GDPR was brought in.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] The legislation refocused companies to look at their own data from a compliance perspective but also revealed future opportunities using personalization and external BI providers to increase market share.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] A Business Intelligence Competency Center (BICC) is a team that supports the use of business intelligence in an organization.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Since 2001, the BICC concept has been refined through implementations in organizations that have adopted BI and related analytical software.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Usage of the term BICC has varied significantly across implementations in different organizations.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] The adoption of the BICC concept has led some organizations to establish units that focus on the use of BI software for decision-making, which may increase the value an organization derives from its BI implementation.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] A BICC coordinates activities and resources to facilitate a fact-based approach to decision-making within an organization.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] It has responsibility for the governance structure for BI and the use of analytical programs, projects, practices, software, and architecture.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] A BICC is responsible for developing plans, priorities, infrastructure, and competencies that can support strategic decision-making using BI and analytical software.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In recent years, knowledge-oriented shared service centers have emerged in many organizations.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Their primary focus has been the offering of analytics and data mining as an internal service across the organization.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Such a center may be referred to as an Analytics Competency Center (ACC), Analytics Center of Excellence, Analytics Service Center, Big Data CoC, or Big Data Lab.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] By the end of 2017, a report by Gartner Research estimated that approximately 25% of large firms had a dedicated ACC unit (or equivalent) for data and analytics.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] In contrast to classic BICCs, these centers do not place emphasis on reporting, historical analysis, and dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] ACCs aim to enhance a company's data capabilities by building expertise in data analytics, formulating a data strategy, identifying use cases for data mining, and promoting the adoption of analytics within the organization.
[src:gcp-looker/business-intelligence] Although BICCs can change into ACCs, new ACC formations can also occur in practice.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In computer information systems, a **dashboard** is a type of graphical user interface which often provides at-a-glance views of data relevant to a particular objective or process through a combination of visualizations and summary information.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In other usage, "dashboard" is another name for "progress report" or "report" and is considered a form of data visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The dashboard is often accessible by a web browser and is typically linked to regularly updating data sources.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are often interactive and facilitate users to explore the data themselves, usually by clicking into elements to view more detailed information.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The term dashboard originates from the automobile dashboard where drivers monitor the major functions at a glance via the instrument panel.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The idea of digital dashboards followed the study of decision support systems in the 1970s.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Early predecessors of the modern business dashboard were first developed in the 1980s in the form of Executive Information Systems (EISs).
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Due to problems primarily with data refreshing and handling, it was soon realized that the approach wasn't practical as information was often incomplete, unreliable, and spread across too many disparate sources.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Thus, EISs hibernated until the 1990s when the information age quickened pace and data warehousing, and online analytical processing (OLAP) allowed dashboards to function adequately.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Despite the availability of enabling technologies, the dashboard use didn't become popular until later in that decade, with the rise of key performance indicators (KPIs), and the introduction of Robert S.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In the late 1990s, Microsoft promoted a concept known as the Digital Nervous System and "digital dashboards" were described as being one leg of that concept.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Today, the use of dashboards forms an important part of Business Performance Management (BPM).
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Initially dashboards were used for monitoring purposes, now with the advancement of technology, dashboards are being used for more analytical purposes.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The use of dashboards has now been incorporating; scenario analysis, drill down capabilities, and presentation format flexibility.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards allow managers to monitor the contribution of the various departments in their organization.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In addition, they enable “rolling up” of information to present a consolidated view across an organization.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] To gauge exactly how well an organization is performing overall, digital dashboards allow you to capture and report specific data points from each department within the organization, thus providing a "snapshot" of performance.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards offers a holistic view of the entire business as it gives the manager a bird's eye view into the performance of sales, data inventory, web traffic, social media analytics and other associated data that is visually presented on a single dashboard.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards lead to better management of marketing/financial strategies as a dashboard for the display of marketing data makes the process of marketing easier and more reliable as compared to doing it manually.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Web analytics play a crucial role in shaping the marketing strategy of many businesses.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards also facilitate for better tracking of sales and financial reporting as the data is more precise and in one area.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Lastly, dashboards offer for better customer service through monitoring because they keep both the managers and the clients updated on the project progress through automated emails and notifications.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards can be broken down according to role and are either strategic, analytical, operational, or informational.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are the 3rd step on the information ladder, demonstrating the conversion of data to increasingly valuable insights.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards support managers at any level in an organization and provide the quick overview that decision-makers need to monitor the health and opportunities of the business.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards of this type focus on high-level measures of performance and forecasts.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards benefit from static snapshots of data (daily, weekly, monthly, and quarterly) that are not constantly changing from one moment to the next.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for analytical purposes often include more context, comparisons, and history, along with subtler performance evaluators.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In addition, analytical dashboards typically support interactions with the data, such as drilling down into the underlying details.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for monitoring operations are often designed differently from those that support strategic decision making or data analysis and often require monitoring of activities and events that are constantly changing and might require attention and response at a moment's notice.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards may be laid out to track the flows inherent in the business processes that they monitor.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Graphically, users may see the high-level processes and then drill down into low-level data.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] This level of detail is often buried deep within the corporate enterprise and otherwise unavailable to the senior executives.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Three main types of digital dashboards dominate the market today: desktop software applications, web-browser-based applications, and desktop applications are also known as desktop widgets.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Both Desktop and Browser-based providers enable the distribution of dashboards via a web browser.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] An example of the latter is web-based-browser Asana, which helps teams orchestrate their work, from daily tasks to strategic cross-functional initiatives.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] With it, teams can manage everything from company objectives to digital transformation to product launches and marketing campaigns.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Specialized dashboards may track all corporate functions.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Examples include human resources, recruiting, sales, operations, security, information technology, project management, customer relationship management, digital marketing and many more departmental dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For a smaller organization like a startup a compact startup scorecard dashboard tracks important activities across lot of domains ranging from social media to sales.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard projects involve business units as the driver and the information technology department as the enabler.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Therefore, the success of dashboard projects depends on the relevancy/importance of information provided within the dashboard.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] This includes the metrics chosen to monitor and the timeliness of the data forming those metrics; data must be up to date and accurate.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Key performance indicators, balanced scorecards, and sales performance figures are some of the content appropriate on business dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards involve the combination of visual and functional features.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] This combination of features helps improve cognition and interpretation.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] A performance dashboard sits at the intersection of two powerful disciplines: business intelligence and performance management.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Therefore, there are different users who could use these dashboards for different reasons.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, a level of workers could look at monitoring inventory while those in more managerial roles can look at lagging measure.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Then executives could utilize the dashboard to evaluate strategic performance against objectives.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Balanced scorecards and dashboards have been linked together as if they were interchangeable.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] However, although both visually display critical information, the difference is in the format: Scorecards can open the quality of an operation while dashboards provide calculated direction.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] A balanced scorecard has what they called a "prescriptive" format.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Each of these sections ensures that a Balanced Scorecard is essentially connected to the businesses critical strategic needs.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The design of a dashboard is more loosely defined.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are usually a series of graphics, charts, gauges and other visual indicators that can be monitored and interpreted.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Even when there is a strategic link, on a dashboard, it may not be noticed as such since objectives are not normally present on dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] However, dashboards can be customized to link their graphs and charts to strategic objectives.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard technology is available "out-of-the-box" from many software providers.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Some companies, however, continue to do in-house development and maintenance of dashboard applications.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, GE Aviation has developed a proprietary software/portal called "Digital Cockpit" to monitor the trends in the aircraft spare parts business.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] A good information design will clearly communicate key information to users and makes supporting information easily accessible.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] There are a few key elements to a good dashboard:.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] A research-based framework for Business Intelligence dashboard design suggests that "cross-visual interactivity" is the most impactful of all features.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards serve as a visual representation for a company to monitor progress and trends, not only among themselves but against other companies as well.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards and visualizations contain data that is updated in real time.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, if the underlying data in an Excel spreadsheet were to change, so would the visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Power BI provides the tools for a user to create different types of visualizations to communicate the data that they are using.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Some examples of these visualizations include graphs, maps, and clustered columns.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Power BI pulls data from Excel that can be used to create dashboards and visualizations.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Whereas Excel does not import data from Power BI.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Excel is typically used for less data and Power BI is more complex.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Power BI can be used to display trends over time.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, a company can create a time plot that shows its costs and revenues over a certain period.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The data can then be arranged to show per day, month, quarter, year, etc.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] This requires simple formatting tools so the data can quickly be changed and compared.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Power BI allows the user to customize their visualizations by adding colors and labels.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In addition, when the user clicks a data point, they are able to understand what the point or selection is showing.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Power BI also has a commonly used map feature where businesses can view their sales and earnings across different states and countries.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Places with the highest amounts of data will appear larger in size.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, a state with the most revenue will be bigger than states with less data.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Power BI is also interactive in that in any type of map a person can expand a specific category to look deeper into the data contained.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Tableau is another program that allows users to create dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Allegedly, One of Tableau's biggest advantages is how much data it can hold.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Tableau can hold an unlimited amount, whereas an Excel spreadsheet has a capacity of 1,048,576 rows.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] However, it is possible to hold and analyze effectively billions of rows in Excel, using its Power Pivot feature.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Tableau has the ability to make interactive dashboards by clicking into a specific point.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, you can have data be displayed within a map.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] By clicking a specific state or city you can get a closer look at the data contained within that location.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Filters and parameters can also be added.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] For example, if one were to analyze revenues across the United States you could set a parameter to only show salaries within a particular range.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Once set, only states within this range will be highlighted.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Excel has many tools that help the user not only implement data but also visualize data.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Excel has many built in functions that can help break down data and also separate data by scenarios.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The user can easily download and add files to their Excel sheets to use for their data.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Other tools Excel offers is the use of conditional formatting and basic pivot tables and charts.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Excel allows the user to reference other cells which ultimately allows for complex computations to be made and conclusions to be drawn from data.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] There are certain guidelines that can be useful when creating dashboards and other visualizations.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The guidelines have a structure that can be followed and that is beginning with reading direction.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] When it comes to how you are arranging your information on your dashboard or a visualization it can be helpful to think about reading direction.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] General reading direction is from left to right and from top to bottom.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Having information flow in this structure will allow others to read and understand your visuals in a more natural structure.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Local proximity is another idea to keep in mind when creating a visual or a dashboard.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Having information in a close proximity can be compared with a better effectiveness and allow users to draw conclusions.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Being able to make sure the user is not being overloaded with information when creating your visual.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Having a few key figures with significant importance can be more helpful compared to having too much information.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] When you have too much information and not a structure to what you are presenting then that is known as a “data graveyard”.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Another aspect to keep in mind while creating visuals that goes along with information overload is the idea of interaction within your visual.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Interacting with the dashboard would allow for further detail to be obtained from the user and allow them to better understand the information on your dashboard.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Chart visualization is an important aspect when creating dashboards, diagrams in particular.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] When you have complex data it can be difficult to come to conclusions from that material and being able to have different visual elements within the dashboard can be helpful in giving a larger overview of the material.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Being able to have a visual reporting system allows multiple processing operations to be carried out and that could increase the effectiveness of decisions.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] There are different types of visualizations that can be seen as more effective depending on the data type and the recipient.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Looking at traditional business graphics in an interactive form is another aspect to keep in mind when creating a dashboard.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Business charts are used mainly in the form of interactive dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] A major advantage of business charts is that the majority of users have an understanding of them.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] There are many connections between dashboards and accounting.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards aid with budgeting, management control, and wage control.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used to present data in a quick and easy to read way.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The ability to present data in a quick way with a visual allows for more data to be processed and understood.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used for performance reports, sales analysis on sectors, and inventory rotation.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards should be quick visualizations that allow decisions to be made quicker than they usually would without the access to dashboard technology.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are also used in accounting decision making settings.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] The data can help prove a change is efficient or inefficient and therefore help with improving systems throughout an organization.
[src:gcp-looker/dashboard-computing] In order for a dashboard to be efficient, the individual creating the dashboard needs to make sure that the information is simple and easy to read and be interpreted.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:gcp-looker/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] A **semantic layer** is a business representation of corporate data that helps end users access data autonomously using common business terms managed through business semantics management.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] A semantic layer maps complex data into familiar business terms such as product, customer, or revenue to offer a unified, consolidated view of data across the organization.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] By using common business terms, rather than data language, to access, manipulate, and organize information, a semantic layer simplifies the complexity of business data.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] Business terms are stored as objects in a semantic layer, which are accessed through business views.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] The semantic layer enables business users to have a common "look and feel" when accessing and analyzing data stored in relational databases and OLAP cubes.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] This is claimed to be core business intelligence (BI) technology that frees users from IT while ensuring correct results.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] Business Views is a multi-tier system that is designed to enable companies to build comprehensive and specific business objects that help report designers and end users access the information they require.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] Business Views is intended to enable people to add the necessary business context to their data islands and link them into a single organized Business View for their organization.
[src:gcp-looker/semantic-layer] Semantic layer maps tables to classes and rows to objects.
